In Linux, there is a special, all-powerful user account named root.
The root user completely bypasses all file permissions. It can read, write, delete, or execute absolutely any file on the system, regardless of what the rules say.

Because it is so powerful, you should never log into a server as root for your normal daily work (one wrong command could delete the whole operating system). Instead, you log in as a normal user (like analyst), and use a special prefix command when you need administrative powers:

sudo stands for "SuperUser Do". It’s the Linux equivalent of right-clicking a program in Windows and selecting "Run as Administrator."

Example: If you try to read a highly protected security file like cat /etc/shadow (where the system hides user password hashes), the system will tell you "Permission Denied."

To bypass this legally, you prefix it with sudo:

Bash
sudo cat /etc/shadow
The system will ask for your password, verify you are authorized to use administrative powers, and then execute the command as if you were the root user.
